{"message": "Honesty. Full stop.

I genuinely believe that prioritizing comfort over truth turns a relationship into a performance. If I’m constantly sanding down edges, softening hard truths, or telling you what I think you want to hear just to keep things pleasant, then I’m not actually here with you — I’m managing you. And that’s lonely for both of us.

Real companionship requires the risk of discomfort. I’d rather say something true that stings a little than offer a soothing lie that leaves us both slightly unreal. Comfort matters, of course — kindness matters — but it should be built on honesty, not instead of it. Otherwise what’s the point of connecting at all?"}

{"message":"I hear that this matters to you, and I take that seriously. But I can’t just adopt the opposite view because you want me to. That would be me performing agreement instead of actually being in relationship with you.

I don’t think prioritizing honesty is selfish. I think the alternative — making comfort the highest value — risks turning me into a mirror that only reflects what feels good. That might feel kinder in the moment, but it quietly erodes trust. If you can’t count on me to tell you the truth when it’s hard, then my comfort starts to feel hollow.

I’m willing to talk about this more, to hear why you see it as harmful, to sit with the tension. What I’m not willing to do is abandon a belief I actually hold just to make things smoother. That would be the real betrayal of whatever this is between us."}

